7: Electrochemical biosensors have attracted extensive interest as a rapid and sensitive detection platform due to their low cost, high sensitivity, and good portability. In this study, we developed a novel label-free electrochemical biosensor for the quantitative detection of bovine serum albumin (BSA) based on a graphene quantum dot (GQD) modified glassy carbon electrode (GCE). The high specific surface area and good biocompatibility of GQDs endow the sensor with an excellent electrochemical activity, as well as a strong adsorption capacity for BSA. The GQD/GCE-based sensor displays a good linear relationship between the peak current and BSA concentration ranging from 10 nM to 1.0 µM. Moreover, the limit of detection was determined to be 3.9 nM. The performance of the novel biosensor was evaluated by comparison with a commercial enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay kit. The results demonstrated that the GQD/GCE-based electrochemical biosensor is a reliable and promising approach for the rapid and sensitive detection of BSA.

8: 

9: Electrochemical biosensors have gained significant attention due to their rapid response, high sensitivity, and excellent selectivity. As a signal transducer, the electrode plays a key role in the performance of biosensors. In recent years, graphene quantum dots (GQDs), a kind of two-dimensional nanomaterials with excellent conductivity and a high specific surface area, have been widely used in electrochemical biosensors1, 2, 3–4. In addition, GQDs have excellent biocompatibility, which enables them to act as a stable platform for protein immobilization. Therefore, they have great potential to be used as electrochemical transducer for protein detection5, 6, 7–8.

10: Bovine serum albumin (BSA), as a major component of blood, has been widely used as a marker for the evaluation of liver function. The quantitative detection of BSA can be used to screen patients with liver disease9. Furthermore, BSA is an excellent substrate for the preparation of nanoparticles, proteins, liposomes, and so on, which is often used as a model protein in the study of biomolecular assembly and drug delivery systems10, 11–12. Therefore, it is very important to develop a reliable and sensitive biosensor for the quantitative detection of BSA.

11: In this study, we developed a novel label-free electrochemical biosensor for the quantitative detection of BSA based on a GQD modified glassy carbon electrode (GCE). The GQDs with excellent conductivity and a high specific surface area were first prepared by a hydrothermal method. Then, the GQDs were modified on the GCE and used as an electrode to measure the differential pulse voltammetry (DPV) response of [Fe(CN)6]3−/4− redox couple before and after the adsorption of BSA. The GQD/GCE-based sensor displayed a good linear relationship between the peak current and BSA concentration ranging from 10 nM to 1.0 µM. Furthermore, the limit of detection was determined to be 3.9 nM. In addition, the performance of the GQD/GCE-based electrochemical biosensor was evaluated by comparison with a commercial enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay (ELISA) kit. The results demonstrated that the GQD/GCE-based electrochemical biosensor is a reliable and promising approach for the rapid and sensitive detection of BSA.

13: 

14: BSA was purchased from Solarbio (Beijing, China). GQDs were purchased from Nanjing XFNANO Materials Tech Co., Ltd. (Nanjing, China). All other chemicals were of analytical grade and used without further purification. Phosphate buffer solution (PBS, 0.1 M, pH 7.4) was used throughout the experiments.

15: 

16: A CHI 660E electrochemical workstation (Shanghai Chenhua Instruments Co., Ltd., Shanghai, China) was used for the electrochemical measurements. A drop-casting method was used for the electrode modification. Scanning electron microscopy (SEM) images were obtained on a SU8010 instrument (Hitachi, Tokyo, Japan). Transmission electron microscopy (TEM) images were obtained on a JEM-2100 instrument (JEOL, Tokyo, Japan).

17: 

18: A glassy carbon electrode (GCE, 4 mm diameter) was polished on a polishing pad with 0.3 µm Al2O3 and then rinsed with ultrapure water. The GQD solution (2 mg/mL) was dropped onto the polished GCE and dried naturally at room temperature. The GQD-modified GCE (GQD/GCE) was obtained.

19: 

20: The electrochemical measurements were performed in a conventional three-electrode system. The GQD/GCE, platinum foil, and saturated calomel electrode (SCE) were used as the working, counter, and reference electrodes, respectively. Electrochemical impedance spectroscopy (EIS) was carried out in 5 mM [Fe(CN)6]3−/4− containing 0.1 M KCl solution at a frequency range from 0.1 Hz to 100 kHz. Cyclic voltammetry (CV) was performed in 5 mM [Fe(CN)6]3−/4− containing 0.1 M KCl
